1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,390
Welcome to this course on connecting AI
agents to systems

2
00:00:03,390 --> 00:00:08,371
So far most of us have used AI to answer
questions and generate content. In this

3
00:00:08,371 --> 00:00:13,352
course, we'll learn how AI can act on our
systems for us — and how to connect it

4
00:00:13,352 --> 00:00:13,793
safely.

5
00:00:14,293 --> 00:00:14,293
<break time="0.5s" />

6
00:00:14,293 --> 00:00:18,319
In this first lesson, we'll explain what
it means to connect an AI agent to a

7
00:00:18,319 --> 00:00:21,073
system, and why it's more than just
adding a feature.

8
00:00:21,073 --> 00:00:21,573
<break time="0.5s" />

9
00:00:21,573 --> 00:00:26,702
Up to now, most of us have used AI in one
mode: we ask, and it answers. We type a

10
00:00:26,702 --> 00:00:30,164
question or paste a document, and we read
the response.

11
00:00:30,164 --> 00:00:35,343
In that mode, the AI sits outside our
systems. It has no hands. A person still

12
00:00:35,343 --> 00:00:39,916
has to take whatever it produces and
carry it into the real workflow.

13
00:00:39,916 --> 00:00:45,198
An AI agent is different. An agent
doesn't just produce text for a person to

14
00:00:45,198 --> 00:00:46,325
act on. It acts.

15
00:00:46,325 --> 00:00:51,105
Given access, it can read a record,
update a field, or trigger the next step

16
00:00:51,105 --> 00:00:55,567
in a process. The AI model is still at
the centre, deciding what to do.

17
00:00:55,567 --> 00:00:59,278
What's new is that it's given tools and
connections that let it reach into our

18
00:00:59,278 --> 00:01:00,675
live systems and change them.

19
00:01:00,675 --> 00:01:07,217
That, in a sentence, is what connecting
means: giving an AI the tools to act, not

20
00:01:07,217 --> 00:01:08,198
just answer.

21
00:01:08,198 --> 00:01:12,517
That difference, between answering and
acting, is what this course is about.

22
00:01:12,517 --> 00:01:16,990
Once an AI can act, and not just
describe, it matters a great deal where

23
00:01:16,990 --> 00:01:21,841
we let it act, where we don't, and who
stays in control. <break time="0.5s" />

24
00:01:21,841 --> 00:01:25,691
It's tempting to treat connecting an
agent as a technical detail that comes

25
00:01:25,691 --> 00:01:27,460
after the real decisions are made.

26
00:01:27,460 --> 00:01:32,282
Connecting an agent doesn't just make one
step faster. It changes who does the

27
00:01:32,282 --> 00:01:37,166
work, what the process can do on its own,
and how information moves through it.

28
00:01:37,166 --> 00:01:41,921
A step that used to wait for a person can
now run by itself. A check that used to

29
00:01:41,921 --> 00:01:46,319
happen in someone's head now happens in
code. An action that used to need a

30
00:01:46,319 --> 00:01:48,637
signature can now happen automatically.

31
00:01:48,637 --> 00:01:53,295
Those are real changes to how the process
behaves, and they affect the steps before

32
00:01:53,295 --> 00:01:55,510
and after, not just the one we touched.

33
00:01:55,510 --> 00:02:00,133
So the worst way to connect an agent is
to put it into whatever step seems

34
00:02:00,133 --> 00:02:03,173
convenient, without a plan, and see what
happens.

35
00:02:03,173 --> 00:02:08,676
The better way is to decide, in advance,
exactly where the agent acts, what it's

36
00:02:08,676 --> 00:02:12,368
allowed to touch, and where a person
stays in control.

37
00:02:12,368 --> 00:02:17,076
That's why we start not from the
technology but from a map of the work,

38
00:02:17,076 --> 00:02:18,219
even a rough one.

39
00:02:18,219 --> 00:02:22,987
A map is just a clear picture of how a
process runs, with a few points marked:

40
00:02:22,987 --> 00:02:27,940
where an agent could add value, where it
must not be allowed to decide, and where

41
00:02:27,940 --> 00:02:29,550
a person stays in control.

42
00:02:29,550 --> 00:02:34,021
This course is about taking one of those
points and turning it into a real,

43
00:02:34,021 --> 00:02:35,773
working, governed connection.

44
00:02:35,773 --> 00:02:36,273
<break time="0.5s" />

45
00:02:36,273 --> 00:02:39,245
In this course, we'll cover three things.

46
00:02:39,245 --> 00:02:44,309
First, how an agent actually connects to
a system, through tools, A.P.I's, and the

47
00:02:44,309 --> 00:02:45,747
Model Context Protocol.

48
00:02:45,747 --> 00:02:50,913
Second, how to judge where a connection
is safe and where it carries real risk,

49
00:02:50,913 --> 00:02:55,813
by separating what an agent reads from
what it can change, and limiting its

50
00:02:55,813 --> 00:02:56,939
access carefully.

51
00:02:56,939 --> 00:03:01,271
Third, how to build oversight and
resilience into the connection, and then

52
00:03:01,271 --> 00:03:03,348
take it safely into live operation.

53
00:03:03,348 --> 00:03:08,011
By the end, we'll be able to take a
single candidate point on a process map

54
00:03:08,011 --> 00:03:12,799
and produce a complete connection design:
the tools it needs, the access it's

55
00:03:12,799 --> 00:03:16,769
allowed, the checkpoints around it, and
the way it fails safely.

56
00:03:16,769 --> 00:03:17,269
<break time="0.5s" />

57
00:03:17,269 --> 00:03:19,498
Let's stop the lesson here.

58
00:03:19,498 --> 00:03:24,184
In this lesson, we first explained what
connecting an AI agent actually means:

59
00:03:24,184 --> 00:03:28,322
giving it the tools to act on our
systems, not just answer questions.

60
00:03:28,322 --> 00:03:32,950
We then saw why that changes how a
process works, not just how fast it runs,

61
00:03:32,950 --> 00:03:37,331
which is why we plan a connection from a
map rather than improvising it.

62
00:03:37,331 --> 00:03:41,835
Finally, we outlined what we'll build
together: a complete, governed connection

63
00:03:41,835 --> 00:03:43,972
design for one part of a process map.

